<p><b>Zygmunt Bauman</b> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1925-11-19"><a href="/wiki/November_19" title="November 19">19 November</a> <a href="/wiki/1925" title="1925">1925</a></span> in <a href="/wiki/Pozna%C5%84" title="Poznań">Poznań</a>) is a <a href="/wiki/Poland" title="Poland">Polish</a> <a href="/wiki/Sociology" title="Sociology">sociologist</a> who, since 1971, has resided in England after being driven out of Poland by an anti-Semitic purge organized by the <a href="/wiki/Polish_United_Workers%27_Party" title="Polish United Workers' Party">Communist Party</a>. Professor of sociology at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Leeds" title="University of Leeds">University of Leeds</a> (and since 1990 <a href="/wiki/Emeritus" title="Emeritus">emeritus</a> professor), Bauman has become best known for his analyses of the links between <a href="/wiki/Modernity" title="Modernity">modernity</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Holocaust" title="Holocaust" class="mw-redirect">Holocaust</a>, and of <a href="/wiki/Postmodernity" title="Postmodernity">postmodern</a> <a href="/wiki/Consumerism" title="Consumerism">consumerism</a>.</p>
